Yes, but I've received these 'gifts' under every subject line I've sent to Child Lit.   
On Nov 4, 2012, at 9:16 AM, June Cummins wrote:

> Dear Sirs and Madams,
> 
> I just checked my spam file and saw there were lots and lots of childlit posts there, all with the same subject line of "New York Times review of Casual Vacancy." Most include pictures of girls showing her very large breasts.  Viewing these, I felt like I was celebrating Mardi Gras in New Orleans.  Only one of these emails find its (her) way into my "inbox."
> 
> It could take a while for Hotmail to respond to Michael's request, and I understand why some people don't want to filter too much through their spam mechanism.  (I check my spam file periodically and do sometimes find important messages or at least those I would have wanted to see there.)  So here's my suggestion.  Try setting up your spam filter /only/ for emails from childlit with the subject line "New York Times review of Casual Vacancy."
> 
> And in the meantime, if you want to talk about that very review of that very book on childlit, use a different subject line.
> 
> I think it's pretty funny that we got these miraculously unguarded photographs while discussing a book in which a famous phrase is "her miraculously unguarded . . . "  (I better not type the final word of the phrase, if I don't want this letter going into your spam files.)
> 
> If I repeated anything someone else has already said (information, advice, feeble jokes, etc.), then I most deeply apologize.
> 
> June C.
> 
